REST doesn&#39;t constrain data formats in this way, but if you consider the
Semantic Web effort as a REST extension (which it&#39;s pretty close to
being), then you might want to publish a resource which returns an RDF
representation that declares which of those other two resources are
available.  Something like;

GET http://university.edu/ws/ HTTP/1.1
Accept: application/rdf+xml

which returns;

&lt;rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf=&quot;...&quot;
         xmlns:my=&quot;...&quot;
         xmlns:rf=&quot;http://www.markbaker.ca/2003/05/rdfforms/&quot;&gt;
  &lt;my:StudentList rdf:about=&quot;http://university.edu/ws/list&quot;/&gt;
  &lt;my:StudentSearch rdf:about=&quot;http://university.edu/ws/search&quot;&gt;
    &lt;rf:indexedBy&gt;
      &lt;rf:IndexParam rf:shortName=&quot;name&quot;&gt;
        &lt;rdf:predicate rdf:resource=&quot;http://university.edu/ws/studentName&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;/rf:IndexParam&gt;
    &lt;/rf:indexedBy&gt;
  &lt;/my:StudentSearch&gt;
&lt;/rdf:RDF&gt;

The use of RDF Forms is just a machine processable way to declare that a
resource can be &quot;searched&quot; via URI/GET parameterization.

Mark.

